To automatically generate a table of contents in a LaTeX document, you can use the `\tableofcontents` command. This command will create a table of contents based on the sections, subsections, and other divisions you have defined in your document. Below is an example of how you can set up a LaTeX document to include a table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% Begin the document
\begin{document}

% Title and author information
\title{Sample Document with Table of Contents}
\author{Author Name}
\date{\today}

% Create the title
\maketitle

% Insert the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Start the main content
\newpage

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section. It provides an overview of the document.

\section{Main Content}
This section contains the main content of the document.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
Details about the first subsection.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
Details about the second subsection.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion section. It summarizes the key points of the document.

% End the document
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:

- **`\documentclass{article}`**: This command specifies the type of document you are creating. In this case, it's an article.
- **`\begin{document}` and `\end{document}`**: These commands mark the beginning and end of the document content.
- **`\title{...}`, `\author{...}`, and `\date{...}`**: These commands define the title, author, and date of the document, respectively.
- **`\maketitle`**: This command generates the title section of the document.
- **`\tableofcontents`**: This command generates the table of contents. It will automatically include all sections, subsections, etc., that are defined in the document.
- **`\section{...}` and `\subsection{...}`**: These commands define sections and subsections within the document. They are automatically included in the table of contents.

When you compile this LaTeX document, the table of contents will be generated based on the sections and subsections you have defined. Note that you may need to compile the document twice for the table of contents to appear correctly, as LaTeX needs to gather information about the sections during the first compilation.

