In LaTeX, you can automatically generate a table of contents using the `\tableofcontents` command. This command is typically used in conjunction with the `\section`, `\subsection`, and `\subsubsection` commands to create entries in the table of contents. Here's a simple example of how to set this up in a LaTeX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% Begin the document
\begin{document}

% Title and author information
\title{Sample Document with Table of Contents}
\author{Author Name}
\date{\today}

% Create the title
\maketitle

% Insert the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Start the sections
\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section. It provides an overview of the document.

\section{Main Content}
This section contains the main content of the document.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
Details about the first subsection.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
Details about the second subsection.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion section. It summarizes the document.

% End the document
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:

1. **Document Class**: We use the `article` class, but you can use other classes like `report` or `book` depending on your needs.

2. **Title and Author**: The `\title`, `\author`, and `\date` commands are used to specify the title, author, and date of the document. The `\maketitle` command then generates the title section.

3. **Table of Contents**: The `\tableofcontents` command is placed where you want the table of contents to appear in the document. It will automatically list all sections, subsections, and subsubsections.

4. **Sections**: The `\section`, `\subsection`, and `\subsubsection` commands are used to create sections and subsections in the document. These will automatically be included in the table of contents.

5. **Compilation**: To ensure the table of contents is generated correctly, you may need to compile your LaTeX document twice. The first compilation writes the section information to the `.toc` file, and the second compilation reads this file to generate the table of contents.

This setup will automatically generate and update the table of contents as you add or modify sections in your document.
